revision.text:
'''Malkin Tower''', sometimes called '''Malking Tower''',{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=37}} was the home of Elizabeth Southerns and her family. Nicknamed Demdike, suggesting that she was "feared and loathed within the community",{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=204}}{{efn|name=Demdike}} Elizabeth was the head of the family and one of the chief protagonists in the [[Pendle witches|Lancashire witch trials]] of 1612, in which her daughter Elizabeth Device, her granddaughter Alizon Device, and her grandson James Device were all found guilty of causing harm by witchcraft and executed at at Gallows Hill<ref name="Executions"/> in Lancaster on 20&nbsp;August 1612; Elizabeth herself died in prison while awaiting trial.{{sfn|Hasted|1993|p=23|ps=}}

Malkin Tower was the venue for perhaps the most well-known alleged witch's coven in English legal history, which took place on [[Good Friday]] 6 April 1612.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=22|ps=}} As a result of an inquiry undertaken by local magistrates into the events of that day eight of those attending the meeting were accused of witchcraft and committed for trial, seven at Lancaster Assizes and one at Yourk Assizes.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=22|ps=}}

The name "Malkin" has several possible derivations: it was a familiar form of the female name "Mary" or "Maud", a term for a poor or shabby woman, and a term for a cat, particularly an old cat as in "grimalkin", or "grey malkin".{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39}} Malkin Tower is believed to have been near the village of [[Newchurch in Pendle]],<ref name=FieldsP60>{{Harvnb|Fields|1998|p=60}}</ref> or possibly in Blacko on the site of present-day Malkin Tower Farm,<ref name=ClaytonP286>{{Harvnb|Clayton|2007|p=286}}</ref> and to have been demolished soon after the trials;<ref name=FieldsP60/> it was not uncommon at the time to quickly demolish empty buildings and recycle the materials.

In December 2011 it was announced that water engineers had unearthed a 17th-century cottage complete with a mummified cat sealed in the walls, close to Lower Black Moss reservoir. Local historians have speculated that it might be the lost Malkin Tower.<ref name="MalkinTower"/>

