The name "Malkin" has several possible derivations: it was a familiar form of the female name "Mary" or "Maud"; a term for a poor or shabby woman; and a term for a cat, particularly an old cat as in "[[grimalkin]]", or "grey malkin".{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39}} Another possibility is a corruption of [[Malt kiln]].{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=268|ps=}}

==Location==
Malkin Tower may have been demolished shortly after the 1612 trials, as it was not uncommon at the time to dismantle empty buildings and recycle the materials, but its location is uncertain.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39A|ps=}}. The account of the trials written by [[Thomas Potts (clerk of court)|Thomas Potts]], clerk to the court, in his ''[[The Wonderfull Discoverie of Witches in the Countie of Lancaster]]'' mentions Malking Tower many times, but only ever describes it as being in the forest of Pendle. The former [[royal forest]] covers a considerable area south and east of [[Pendle Hill]], extending to edges of the towns of [[Burnley]], [[Colne]] and [[Padiham]].

One contender is in the civil parish of [[Blacko]] on the site of present-day Malkin Tower Farm;{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=286|ps=}} another is somewhere near the village of [[Newchurch in Pendle]].{{sfn|Fields|1998|p=60|ps=}} In December 2011 it was announced that water engineers had unearthed a 17th-century cottage complete with a mummified cat sealed in the walls, close to [[Black Moss Reservoirs|Lower Black Moss reservoir]], which local historians have speculated might be the lost Malkin Tower.<ref name="MalkinTower"/>

