Malkin Tower may have been demolished shortly after the 1612 trials, as it was not uncommon at the time to dismantle empty buildings{{efn|name=Empty|The building accommodated only Alizon Device and her grandmother; Alizon was hanged and her grandmother died in prison awaiting trial.}} and recycle the materials, but its location is uncertain.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39A|ps=}} The account of the trials written by [[Thomas Potts (clerk of court)|Thomas Potts]], clerk to the court, in his ''[[The Wonderfull Discoverie of Witches in the Countie of Lancaster]]'' mentions Malking Tower many times, but only ever describes it as being in the forest of Pendle. The former [[royal forest]] covers a considerable area south and east of [[Pendle Hill]], extending to edges of the towns of [[Burnley]], [[Colne]] and [[Padiham]].

One contender is in the civil parish of [[Blacko]] on the site of present-day Malkin Tower Farm;{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=286|ps=}} another is somewhere near the village of [[Newchurch in Pendle]].{{sfn|Fields|1998|p=60|ps=}} It is likely that despite its name Malkin Tower was in reality a simple cottage, rather than a tower.<ref name="Guardian"/> A potential candidate was discovered in December 2011, when it was announced that water engineers had unearthed a 17th-century cottage complete with a mummified cat sealed in the walls, close to [[Black Moss Reservoirs|Lower Black Moss reservoir]], which local historians have speculated might be the lost Malkin Tower.<ref name="MalkinTower"/>{{-}}

