[[Category:History of Lancashire]]

'''Malkin Tower''', sometimes called '''Malking Tower''',{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=37}} was the home of Elizabeth Southerns, also known as Demdike,{{efn|name=Demdike|"Demdike" is derived from "devil woman", suggesting that Elizabeth Southerns was "feared and loathed within the community".{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=204}}}} and her granddaughter Alizon Device.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=38|ps=}} Elizabeth and Alizon were two of the chief protagonists in the [[Pendle witches|Lancashire witch trials]] of 1612, in which they and two other members of their family&nbsp;– Alizon's daughter Elizabeth Device and her son James Device&nbsp;– were all found guilty of causing harm by witchcraft and executed at at Gallows Hill<ref name="Executions"/> in Lancaster on 20&nbsp;August 1612; Elizabeth herself, who was in her eighties, died in prison while awaiting trial.{{sfn|Hasted|1993|p=23|ps=}}

Malkin Tower was the venue for perhaps the most well-known alleged witch's coven in English legal history, which took place on [[Good Friday]] 6 April 1612.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=22|ps=}} As a result of an inquiry undertaken by local magistrates into the events of that day eight of those attending the meeting were accused of witchcraft and committed for trial, seven at Lancaster Assizes and one at York Assizes.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=22|ps=}}

The name "Malkin" has several possible derivations: it was a familiar form of the female name "Mary" or "Maud"; a term for a poor or shabby woman; and a term for a cat, particularly an old cat as in "[[grimalkin]]", or "grey malkin".{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39}} Another possibility is a corruption of [[Malt kiln]].{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=268|ps=}}

