==External links==
*{{gutenberg|no=18253|name=The Wonderfull Discoverie of Witches in the Countie of Lancaster}} (1613)

[[Category:History of Lancashire]]

'''Malkin Tower''', sometimes called '''Malking Tower''',{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=37}} or '''Mocking Tower''',{{sfn|Poole|2002|p=13}} was the home of Elizabeth Southerns, also known as Demdike,{{efn|name=Demdike|"Demdike" is derived from "devil woman", suggesting that Elizabeth Southerns was "feared and loathed within the community".{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=204}}}} and her granddaughter Alizon Device.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=38|ps=}} Elizabeth and Alizon were two of the chief protagonists in the [[Pendle witches|Lancashire witch trials]] of 1612, in which they and two other members of their family&nbsp;– Alizon's daughter Elizabeth Device and her son James Device&nbsp;– were all found guilty of causing harm by witchcraft and executed at at Gallows Hill<ref name="Executions"/> in Lancaster on 20&nbsp;August 1612; Elizabeth herself, who was in her eighties, died in prison while awaiting trial.{{sfn|Hasted|1993|p=23|ps=}}

Malkin Tower was the venue for perhaps the most well-known alleged witch's coven in English legal history, which took place on [[Good Friday]] 6 April 1612.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=22|ps=}} As a result of an inquiry undertaken by local magistrates into the events of that day eight of those attending the meeting were accused of witchcraft and committed for trial, seven at Lancaster Assizes and one at York Assizes.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=22|ps=}}

==Name==
The name "Malkin" has several possible derivations: it was a familiar form of the female name "Mary" or "Maud"; a term for a poor or shabby woman; and a term for a cat, particularly an old cat as in "[[grimalkin]]", or "grey malkin".{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39}} "Malkin" was also an old northern English name for a [[hare]], into which the witches were said to be able to transfigure.{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48}}<ref name="PrestonChronicle"/> It has also been suggested that the name was a combination of "mal" and "kin" as a swipe at the family that resided there,{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48}}{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14}} although local historian Arthur Douglas considered this unlikely due to the poor education of the people in the area during that time.{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48}} Another possibility is a corruption of [[Malt kiln]],{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48}}{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=268|ps=}} or "mawkin", an old word for a lower-class woman or a slut.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14}}

It is likely that despite its name Malkin Tower was in reality a simple cottage, rather than a tower.<ref name="Guardian"/> Historian W. R. Mitchell proposes that the witches' home was originally a small farm building, perhaps a shelter for fodder or livestock, which was converted into poor-quality living accommodation.{{sfn|Mitchell|1984|p=25}} It is therefore possible that "Tower" was in fact a sarcastic name given by local residents.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14}}

==Location==
[[File:Upper and Lower Black Moss Reservoir - geograph.org.uk - 106540.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Lower Black Moss Reservoir (on the left), one of the suggested sites for the location of Malkin Tower|alt=photograph]]
Malkin Tower may have been demolished shortly after the 1612 trials, as it was not uncommon at the time to dismantle empty buildings{{efn|name=Empty|The building accommodated only Alizon Device and her grandmother; Alizon was hanged and her grandmother died in prison awaiting trial. The other members of the family lived in a smallholding that belonged to John Device, Elizabeth Device's deceased husband.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=38|ps=}}}} and recycle the materials, but its location is uncertain.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39|ps=}} The account of the trials written by [[Thomas Potts (clerk of court)|Thomas Potts]], clerk to the court, in his ''[[The Wonderfull Discoverie of Witches in the Countie of Lancaster]]'' mentions Malking Tower many times, but only ever describes it as being in the forest of Pendle. The former [[royal forest]] covers a considerable area south and east of [[Pendle Hill]], extending to edges of the towns of [[Burnley]], [[Colne]] and [[Padiham]].

One contender is in the civil parish of [[Blacko]] on the site of present-day Malkin Tower Farm;{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=286|ps=}} old masonry found in one of the field walls is said to be from the remains of the building.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14}} Local folklore in the parish holds that the remains of Malkin Tower are buried in a field behind the Cross Gaits Inn public house, and the tower is featured on the inn's sign.{{sfn|Davitt|2006|p=22}} Another possible location is somewhere near the village of [[Newchurch in Pendle]];{{sfn|Fields|1998|p=60|ps=}} Douglas claims there is "persuasive" evidence that the area now known as Sadler's Farm was the site of Malkin Tower.{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48}} Archaeological excavations have taken place in several locations around the Pendle Forest area, including Newchurch, although nothing has yet been found.{{sfn|Mitchell|1984|p=25}}

A potential candidate was discovered in December 2011, when it was announced that water engineers had unearthed a 17th-century cottage complete with a mummified cat sealed in the walls, close to [[Black Moss Reservoirs|Lower Black Moss reservoir]], which local historians have speculated might be the lost Malkin Tower.<ref name="MalkinTower"/>{{-}}

