One contender is in the civil parish of [[Blacko]] on the site of present-day Malkin Tower Farm;{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=286|ps=}} old masonry found in one of the field walls is said to be from the remains of the building.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14}} Local folklore in the parish holds that the remains of Malkin Tower are buried in a field behind the Cross Gaits Inn public house, and the tower is featured on the inn's sign.{{sfn|Davitt|2006|p=22}} Another possible location is somewhere near the village of [[Newchurch in Pendle]];{{sfn|Fields|1998|p=60|ps=}} Douglas claims there is "persuasive" evidence that the area now known as Sadler's Farm was the site of Malkin Tower.{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48}} Archaeological excavations have taken place in several locations around the Pendle Forest area, including Newchurch, although nothing has yet been found.{{sfn|Mitchell|1984|p=25}}

A potential candidate was discovered in December 2011, when it was announced that water engineers had unearthed a 17th-century cottage complete with a mummified cat sealed in the walls, close to [[Black Moss Reservoirs|Lower Black Moss reservoir]], which local historians have speculated might be the lost Malkin Tower.<ref name="MalkinTower"/>{{-}}

