==Location==
[[File:Upper and Lower Black Moss Reservoir - geograph.org.uk - 106540.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Lower Black Moss Reservoir (on the left), one of the suggested sites for the location of Malkin Tower|alt=photograph]]
Malkin Tower may have been demolished shortly after the 1612 trials, as it was not uncommon at the time to dismantle empty buildings{{efn|name=Empty|The building accommodated only Alizon Device and her grandmother; Alizon was hanged and her grandmother died in prison awaiting trial. The other members of the family lived in a smallholding that had belonged to John Device, Elizabeth Device's deceased husband.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=38|ps=}}}} and recycle the materials, but its location is uncertain.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39|ps=}} The account of the trials written by [[Thomas Potts (clerk of court)|Thomas Potts]], clerk to the court, in his ''[[The Wonderfull Discoverie of Witches in the Countie of Lancaster]]'' mentions Malking Tower many times, but only ever describes it as being in the forest of Pendle. The former [[royal forest]] covers a considerable area south and east of [[Pendle Hill]], extending to edges of the towns of [[Burnley]], [[Colne]] and [[Padiham]].

One contender is in the civil parish of [[Blacko]] on the site of present-day Malkin Tower Farm;{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=286|ps=}} old masonry found in one of the field walls is said to be from the remains of the building.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14|ps=}} Local folklore in the parish holds that the remains of Malkin Tower are buried in a field behind the nearby Cross Gaits Inn [[public house]], and the tower used to be featured on the inn's sign.{{sfn|Davitt|2006|p=22|ps=}} The primary source of evidence supporting this location seems to be that a hollow in the hillside east of the farm is known as Mawkin hole.{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=279|ps=}} It is suggested that this is the same place mentioned in the 16th century halmote court records for the [[manor]] of Colne, called Mawkin Yarde{{efn|name=Mawkin|Spelt variously: Malkynyerd, Malkenyerd, Malkynyerde, Mawkyn-yarde, Mawkin Yarde {{sfn|Farrer|1897|p=237, 266, 241, 458, 466|ps=}}}} and described as “in the north of Colne”.{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=286|ps=}} However this also causes a problem as by definition anywhere inside the manor of Colne would be outside the forest of Pendle. The site is also several miles from any of the traceable locations mentioned at the trial.

Another possible location is somewhere near the village of [[Newchurch in Pendle]];{{sfn|Fields|1998|p=60|ps=}} Douglas claims there is "persuasive" evidence that an area near Sadler's Farm (now known as Shekinah Christian Centre) was the site of Malkin Tower.{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48}} Archaeological excavations have taken place in several locations around the Pendle Forest area, including Newchurch, but nothing has yet been found.{{sfn|Mitchell|1984|p=25|ps=}}

