On [[Good Friday]], 6 April 1612, Malkin Tower was the venue for perhaps the most well-known alleged witch's coven in English legal history.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=22|ps=}} As a result of an inquiry undertaken by local magistrates into the events of that day eight of those attending the meeting were accused of witchcraft and committed for trial, seven at Lancaster Assizes and one at York Assizes.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=22|ps=}}

==Name==
The name "Malkin" has several possible derivations: it was a familiar form of the female name "Mary" or "Maud"; a term for a poor or shabby woman; and a term for a cat, particularly an old cat as in "[[grimalkin]]", or "grey malkin".{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39|ps=}} "Malkin" was also an old northern English name for a [[hare]], into which the witches were said to be able to transfigure.{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}}<ref name="PrestonChronicle"/> It has also been suggested that the name was a combination of "mal" and "kin" as a swipe at the family that resided there,{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}}{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14|ps=}} which local historian Arthur Douglas considered unlikely owing to the poor education of people in the area at that time.{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}} Another possibility is a corruption of [[Malt kiln]],{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}}{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=268|ps=}} or "mawkin", an old word for a lower-class woman or slut.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14|ps=}}

It is likely that despite its name Malkin Tower was in reality a simple cottage, rather than a tower.<ref name="Guardian"/> Historian W. R. Mitchell suggests that it was originally a small farm building, perhaps a shelter for fodder or livestock, which was converted into poor-quality living accommodation.{{sfn|Mitchell|1984|p=25|ps=}} It is therefore possible that "Tower" was in fact a sarcastic name given by local residents.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14|ps=}}

==Location==
[[File:Upper and Lower Black Moss Reservoir - geograph.org.uk - 106540.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Lower Black Moss Reservoir (on the left), one of the suggested sites for the location of Malkin Tower|alt=photograph]]
Malkin Tower may have been demolished shortly after the 1612 trials, as it was not uncommon at the time to dismantle empty buildings and recycle the materials,{{efn|name=Empty|The building accommodated only Alizon Device and her grandmother; Alizon was hanged and her grandmother died in prison awaiting trial. The other members of the family lived in a smallholding that had belonged to John Device, Elizabeth Device's deceased husband.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=38|ps=}}}} but its location is uncertain.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39|ps=}} The account of the trials written by [[Thomas Potts (clerk of court)|Thomas Potts]], clerk to the court, in his ''[[The Wonderfull Discoverie of Witches in the Countie of Lancaster]]'' mentions Malking Tower many times, but only describes it as being in the Forest of Pendle, a former [[royal forest]] that covered a considerable area south and east of [[Pendle Hill]], extending almost to the towns of [[Burnley]], [[Colne]] and [[Padiham]].

One contender is in the civil parish of [[Blacko]], on the site of present-day Malkin Tower Farm;{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=286|ps=}} old masonry found in one of the field walls is said to be from the remains of the building.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14|ps=}} Local folklore in the parish holds that the remains of Malkin Tower are buried in a field behind the nearby Cross Gaits Inn [[public house]], and the tower used to be featured on the inn's sign.{{sfn|Davitt|2006|p=22|ps=}} The primary source of evidence supporting this location seems to be that a hollow in the hillside east of the farm is known as Mawkin hole.{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=279|ps=}} It is suggested that this is the same place mentioned in the 16th-century halmote court records for the [[manor]] of Colne as Mawkin Yarde,{{efn|name=Mawkin|Spelt variously: Malkynyerd, Malkenyerd, Malkynyerde, Mawkyn-yarde, Mawkin Yarde {{sfn|Farrer|1897|p=237, 266, 241, 458, 466|ps=}}}} and described as being "in the north of Colne".{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=286|ps=}} However this also causes a problem as by definition anywhere inside the manor of Colne would be outside the Forest of Pendle. The site is also several miles from any of the traceable locations mentioned at the trial.

Another possible location is somewhere near the village of [[Newchurch in Pendle]];{{sfn|Fields|1998|p=60|ps=}} Douglas claims there is "persuasive" evidence that an area near Sadler's Farm (now known as Shekinah Christian Centre) was the site of Malkin Tower.{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48}} Archaeological excavations have taken place in several locations around the Pendle Forest area, including Newchurch, but nothing has yet been found.{{sfn|Mitchell|1984|p=25|ps=}}

A further potential candidate for the lost Malkin Tower was announced in December 2011, after water engineers unearthed a 17th-century cottage complete with a mummified cat sealed in the walls, close to [[Black Moss Reservoirs|Lower Black Moss reservoir]].<ref name="MalkinTower"/>{{-}}

