[[File:Upper and Lower Black Moss Reservoir - geograph.org.uk - 106540.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Lower Black Moss Reservoir (on the left), one of the suggested sites for the location of Malkin Tower|alt=photograph]]
'''Malkin Tower''', sometimes called '''Malking Tower''',{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=37|ps=}} or '''Mocking Tower''',{{sfn|Poole|2002|p=13|ps=}} was the home of Elizabeth Southerns, also known as Demdike,{{efn|name=Demdike|"Demdike" is derived from "devil woman", suggesting that Elizabeth Southerns was "feared and loathed within the community".{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=204|ps=}}}} and her granddaughter Alizon Device,{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=38|ps=}} two of the chief protagonists in the [[Pendle witches|Lancashire witch trials]] of 1612.<ref name="Executions"/>

On [[Good Friday]], 6 April 1612, Malkin Tower was the venue for perhaps the most well-known alleged witch's coven in English legal history.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=22|ps=}}

==History==
===Toponymy===
The name "Malkin" has several possible derivations: it was a familiar form of the female name "Mary", or "Maud", and a term for a poor or shabby woman;{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39|ps=}} the similar "mawkin" was a word used to describe a lower-class woman or slut.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14|ps=}} "Malkin" was also used as a term for a cat, particularly an old cat, as in "[[grimalkin]]", or "grey malkin",{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39|ps=}} and was an old northern English name for a [[hare]], into which witches were said to be able to transfigure.{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}}<ref name="PrestonChronicle"/> It has also been suggested that the name was a combination of "mal" and "kin" as a slight to the residents of Malkin Tower,{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14|ps=}}{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}} which local historian Arthur Douglas considers unlikely owing to the poor education of people in the area at that time.{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}} Another possibility is a corruption of [[malt kiln]].{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}}{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=268|ps=}}

Despite its name, Malkin Tower was probably a simple cottage rather than a tower.<ref name="Guardian"/> Historian W. R. Mitchell suggests that it was originally a small farm building, perhaps a shelter for fodder or livestock, which was converted into poor-quality living accommodation.{{sfn|Mitchell|1984|p=25|ps=}} "Tower" may therefore have been a sarcastic name given by local residents.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14|ps=}}

===Association with witches===
As a consequence of a chance encounter Alizon Device had on 21 March 1612 with John Law, a pedlar from Halifax, she and her grandmother were summoned to the home of local magistrate Roger Nowell on suspicion of causing harm by witchcraft; Law had collapsed shortly after meeting Alizon, and his son had accused her of being responsible.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=10|ps=}} Both she and her grandmother were subsequently arrested and detained in Lancaster Gaol, along with two other women.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=16|ps=}} Friends of the Demdike family met at Malkin Tower on 6 April 1612, allegedly to plot the escape of the four gaoled women by blowing up Lancaster Castle. When Nowell learned of the meeting he concluded after examining Alizon Device's "mentally sub-normal" brother, James, that Malkin Tower had been the scene of a witches' coven, and that all who attended were witches.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|pp=16–18|ps=}} Eight were subsequently accused of witchcraft and committed for trial, seven at [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]] [[Assizes]] and one at York.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=22|ps=}}

==Location==
Malkin Tower may have been demolished shortly after the 1612 trials, as it was not uncommon at the time to dismantle empty buildings and recycle the materials,{{efn|name=Empty|The building accommodated only Alizon Device and her grandmother; Alizon was hanged and her grandmother died in prison awaiting trial. The other members of the family lived in a smallholding that had belonged to John Device, Elizabeth Device's deceased husband.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=38|ps=}}}} but its location is uncertain.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39|ps=}} The account of the trials written by [[Thomas Potts (clerk of court)|Thomas Potts]], clerk to the court, in his ''[[The Wonderfull Discoverie of Witches in the Countie of Lancaster]]'' mentions Malking Tower many times, but only describes it as being in the Forest of Pendle, a former [[royal forest]] that covered a considerable area south and east of [[Pendle Hill]], extending almost to the towns of [[Burnley]], [[Colne]] and [[Padiham]].

One contender is in the civil parish of [[Blacko]], on the site of present-day Malkin Tower Farm;{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=286|ps=}} old masonry found in one of the field walls is said to be from the remains of the building.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14|ps=}} Local folklore in the parish holds that the remains of Malkin Tower are buried in a field behind the nearby Cross Gaits Inn [[public house]], and the tower used to be featured on the inn's sign.{{sfn|Davitt|2006|p=22|ps=}} The primary source of evidence supporting this location seems to be that a hollow in the hillside east of the farm is known as Mawkin hole.{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=279|ps=}} It is suggested that this is the same place mentioned in the 16th-century halmote court records for the [[manor]] of Colne as Mawkin Yarde,{{efn|name=Mawkin|Spelt variously: Malkynyerd, Malkenyerd, Malkynyerde, Mawkyn-yarde, Mawkin Yarde {{sfn|Farrer|1897|pp=237, 266, 241, 458, 466|ps=}}}} and described as being "in the north of Colne".{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=286|ps=}} However this also causes a problem as by definition anywhere inside the manor of Colne would be outside the Forest of Pendle. The site is also several miles from any of the traceable locations mentioned at the trial.

Another possible location is somewhere near the village of [[Newchurch in Pendle]];{{sfn|Fields|1998|p=60|ps=}} Douglas claims there is "persuasive" evidence that an area near Sadler's Farm (now known as Shekinah Christian Centre) was the site of Malkin Tower.{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48}} Archaeological excavations have taken place in several locations around the Pendle Forest area, including Newchurch, but nothing has been found.{{sfn|Mitchell|1984|p=25|ps=}}

A further potential candidate for the lost Malkin Tower was announced in December 2011, after water engineers unearthed a 17th-century cottage complete with a mummified cat sealed in the walls, close to [[Black Moss Reservoirs|Lower Black Moss reservoir]].<ref name="MalkinTower"/>{{-}}

