As a consequence of a chance encounter Alizon Device had on 21 March 1612 with John Law, a pedlar from Halifax, she and her grandmother were summoned to the home of local magistrate Roger Nowell on suspicion of causing harm by witchcraft; Law had collapsed shortly after meeting Alizon, and his son had accused her of being responsible.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=10|ps=}} Both she and her grandmother were subsequently arrested and detained in Lancaster Gaol, along with two other women.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=16|ps=}} Friends of the Demdike family met at Malkin Tower on 6 April 1612, allegedly to plot the escape of the four gaoled women by blowing up Lancaster Castle. When Nowell learned of the meeting he concluded after examining Alizon Device's "mentally sub-normal" brother, James, that Malkin Tower had been the scene of a witches' coven, and that all who attended were witches.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|pp=16–18|ps=}} Eight were subsequently accused of witchcraft and committed for trial, seven at [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]] [[Assizes]] and one at York.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=22|ps=}}

==Location==
The location of Malkin Tower is uncertain.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39|ps=}} It may have been demolished shortly after the 1612 trials, as it was not uncommon at the time to dismantle empty buildings and recycle the materials.{{efn|name=Empty|The building accommodated only Alizon Device and her grandmother; Alizon was hanged and her grandmother died in prison awaiting trial. The other members of the family lived in a smallholding that had belonged to John Device, Elizabeth Device's deceased husband.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=38|ps=}}}} The building may also have been destroyed in order to eradicate the "melancholy associations" of the place.{{sfn|Peel|Southern|1985|p=156|ps=}} The account of the trials written by [[Thomas Potts (clerk of court)|Thomas Potts]], clerk to the court, in his ''[[The Wonderfull Discoverie of Witches in the Countie of Lancaster]]'' mentions Malking Tower many times, but only describes it as being in the Forest of Pendle, a former [[royal forest]] that covered a considerable area south and east of [[Pendle Hill]], extending almost to the towns of [[Burnley]], [[Colne]] and [[Padiham]].

[[File:Blacko Tower - geograph.org.uk - 1138193.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Stansfield Tower, Blacko, a Victorian [[folly]] often confused with Malkin Tower{{sfn|Peel|Southern|1985|p=157|ps=}}|alt=photograph]]
One contender is in the civil parish of [[Blacko]], on the site of present-day Malkin Tower Farm;{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=286|ps=}} old masonry found in one of the field walls is said to be from the remains of the building.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14|ps=}} Local folklore in the parish holds that the remains of Malkin Tower are buried in a field behind the nearby Cross Gaits Inn [[public house]]; the tower used to be featured on the inn's sign.{{sfn|Davitt|2006|p=22|ps=}} The primary evidence supporting this location seems to be that a hollow in the hillside east of the farm is known as Mawkin Hole.{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=279|ps=}} It is suggested that this is the same place mentioned in the 16th-century halmote court records for the [[manor]] of Colne as Mawkin Yarde,{{efn|name=Mawkin|Spelt variously: Malkynyerd, Malkenyerd, Malkynyerde, Mawkyn-yarde, Mawkin Yarde {{sfn|Farrer|1897|pp=237, 266, 241, 458, 466|ps=}}}} described as being "in the north of Colne",{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=286|ps=}} but anywhere inside the manor of Colne would be outside the Forest of Pendle. The site is also several miles from any of the traceable locations mentioned at the trial.{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}}

Another possible location is somewhere near the village of [[Newchurch in Pendle]].{{sfn|Fields|1998|p=60|ps=}} Douglas claims there is "persuasive" evidence that an area near Sadler's Farm (now known as Shekinah Christian Centre) was the site of Malkin Tower; there were numerous alleged sightings of witchcraft in the area, and it was in the vicinity of other locations named during the trial, such as Greenhead, [[Barley, Lancashire|Barley]] and [[Roughlee]].{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}} Others related to the trials were also known to have lived in the area; alleged witches Jane and John Bulcock resided at Moss End Farm in Newchurch, while John Nutter, whose cows were claimed to have been bewitched, lived at the neighbouring Bull Hole Farm. Southerns' son Christopher Holgate also lived nearby. However, neither the deeds of Sadler's Farm, which date back to the 17th century, nor contemporary maps of the region mention Malkin Tower or any fields in which it may have stood.{{sfn|Peel|Southern|1985|p=155|ps=}}

Archaeological excavations have taken place in several locations around the Pendle Forest area, including Newchurch, but nothing has been found.{{sfn|Mitchell|1984|p=25|ps=}} A potential candidate for the lost Malkin Tower was announced in December 2011, after water engineers unearthed a 17th-century cottage complete with a mummified cat sealed in the walls, close to [[Black Moss Reservoirs|Lower Black Moss reservoir]] near Barley.<ref name="MalkinTower"/>{{-}}

