==External links==
*{{gutenberg|no=18253|name=The Wonderfull Discoverie of Witches in the Countie of Lancaster}} (1613)

[[Category:History of Lancashire]]

[[File:Upper and Lower Black Moss Reservoir - geograph.org.uk - 106540.jpg|right|thumb|250px|[[Black Moss Reservoirs|Lower Black Moss Reservoir]] (on the left), one of the suggested sites for the location of Malkin Tower|alt=rolling unwooded landscape]]
'''Malkin Tower''', sometimes called '''Malking Tower''',{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=37|ps=}} or '''Mocking Tower''',{{sfn|Poole|2002|p=13|ps=}} was the home of Elizabeth Southerns, also known as Demdike,{{efn|name=Demdike|"Demdike" is derived from "devil woman", suggesting that Elizabeth Southerns was "feared and loathed within the community".{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=204|ps=}}}} and her granddaughter Alizon Device,{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=38|ps=}} two of the chief protagonists in the [[Pendle witches|Lancashire witch trials]] of 1612.<ref name="Executions"/>

On [[Good Friday]], 6 April 1612, Malkin Tower was the venue for perhaps the most well-known alleged witch's coven in English legal history.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=22|ps=}} Eight of those who attended were arrested and tried for causing harm by witchcraft, seven of whom were found guilty and executed. The house was demolished shortly after the trials and forgotten. The only firm evidence of its location comes from the official account by the clerk to the court, [[The Wonderfull Discoverie of Witches in the Countie of Lancaster|Thomas Potts]], who says simply that it was in the Forest of Pendle. Despite several archaeological excavations in the area no remains have yet been discovered.

Several explanations have been suggested for the origins of the word "Malkin", but despite its name Malkin Tower was likely to have been a simple cottage rather than a tower.

==History==
===Toponymy===
{{Quote box |width=28em |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center |quote=Malkin's Tower, a little cottage where<br/>Reporte makes caitive witches meete to swear<br/>Their homage to ye devil.{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=273|ps=}}
|source=[[Richard James (scholar)|Richard James]] c.&nbsp;1633}}
The name "Malkin" has several possible derivations: it was a familiar form of the female name "Mary", or "Maud", and a term for a poor or shabby woman;{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39|ps=}} the similar "mawkin" was a word used to describe a lower-class woman or slut.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14|ps=}} "Malkin" was also used as a term for a cat, particularly an old cat, as in "[[grimalkin]]", or "grey malkin",{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39|ps=}} and was an old northern English name for a [[hare]],{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}} into which witches were said to be able to transfigure.<ref name="PrestonChronicle"/> It has also been suggested that the name was a combination of "mal" and "kin" as a slight to the residents of Malkin Tower,{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14|ps=}}{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}} which local historian Arthur Douglas considers unlikely owing to the poor education of people in the area at that time.{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}} Another possibility is a corruption of [[malt kiln]],{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}}{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=268|ps=}} which is supported by Alizon Device's claim that the family of Anne Whittle (also known as Chattox) had broken into their "fire house".{{sfn|Peel|Southern|1985|p=154|ps=}}

Authors have speculated on a range of buildings that could account for the "Tower" title. It may have incorporated a [[Normans|Norman]] [[peel tower]], built as defence from Scottish raiders{{sfn|Fields|1998|p=60|ps=}} or possibly a disused poacher lookout.{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=268|ps=}} It is more likely, however, that despite its name, Malkin Tower was a simple cottage.<ref name="Guardian"/> Historian W. R. Mitchell suggests that it was originally a small farm building, perhaps a shelter for fodder or livestock, which was converted into poor-quality living accommodation.{{sfn|Mitchell|1984|p=25|ps=}} Poverty was not uncommon among the residents of the Forest of Pendle, hence the building was likely to have been no more than a hovel,{{sfn|Eyre|1986|p=13|ps=}} and "tower" may therefore have been a sarcastic name given by local residents.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14|ps=}} In any case, it is almost certain that Southerns and Device did not own Malkin Tower, but were tenants of the property.{{sfn|Peel|Southern|1985|p=155}}

===Association with witches===
As a consequence of a chance encounter Alizon Device had on 21 March 1612 with John Law, a pedlar from Halifax, she and her grandmother were summoned to the home of local magistrate Roger Nowell on suspicion of causing harm by witchcraft; Law had collapsed shortly after meeting Alizon, and his son had accused her of being responsible.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=10|ps=}} Both she and her grandmother were subsequently arrested and detained in Lancaster Gaol, along with two other women.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=16|ps=}} Friends of the Demdike family met at Malkin Tower on 6 April 1612, allegedly to plot the escape of the four gaoled women by blowing up Lancaster Castle. When Nowell learned of the meeting he concluded after examining Alizon Device's "mentally sub-normal" brother, James, that Malkin Tower had been the scene of a witches' coven, and that all who attended were witches.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|pp=16–18|ps=}} Eight were subsequently accused of witchcraft and committed for trial, seven at [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]] [[Assizes]] and one at York.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=22|ps=}}

==Location==
The location of Malkin Tower is uncertain.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=39|ps=}} It may have been demolished shortly after the 1612 trials, as it was not uncommon at the time to dismantle empty buildings and recycle the materials.{{efn|name=Empty|The building accommodated only Alizon Device and her grandmother; Alizon was hanged and her grandmother died in prison awaiting trial. The other members of the family lived in a smallholding that had belonged to John Device, Elizabeth Device's deceased husband.{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=38|ps=}}}} The building may also have been destroyed in order to eradicate the "melancholy associations" of the place.{{sfn|Peel|Southern|1985|p=156|ps=}} The account of the trials written by [[Thomas Potts (clerk of court)|Thomas Potts]], clerk to the court, in his ''[[The Wonderfull Discoverie of Witches in the Countie of Lancaster]]'' mentions Malking Tower many times, but only describes it as being in the Forest of Pendle, a former [[royal forest]] that covered a considerable area south and east of [[Pendle Hill]], extending almost to the towns of [[Burnley]], [[Colne]] and [[Padiham]].

[[File:Blacko Tower - geograph.org.uk - 1138193.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Stansfield Tower, Blacko, a Victorian [[folly]] often confused with Malkin Tower{{sfn|Peel|Southern|1985|p=157|ps=}}|alt=Prominent structure on a hill]]
One contender is in the civil parish of [[Blacko]], on the site of present-day Malkin Tower Farm;{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=286|ps=}} old masonry found in one of the field walls is said to be from the remains of the building.{{sfn|Catlow|1986|pp=13–14|ps=}} Local folklore in the parish holds that the remains of Malkin Tower are buried in a field behind the nearby Cross Gaits Inn [[public house]]; the tower used to be featured on the inn's sign.{{sfn|Davitt|2006|p=22|ps=}} The primary evidence supporting this location seems to be that a hollow in the hillside east of the farm is known as Mawkin Hole.{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=279|ps=}} It is suggested that this is the same place mentioned in the 16th-century halmote court records for the [[manor]] of Colne as Mawkin Yarde,{{efn|name=Mawkin|Spelt variously: Malkynyerd, Malkenyerd, Malkynyerde, Mawkyn-yarde, Mawkin Yarde{{sfn|Farrer|1897|pp=237, 266, 241, 458, 466|ps=}}}} described as being "in the north of Colne",{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=286|ps=}} but anywhere inside the manor of Colne would have been outside the Forest of Pendle. The site is also several miles from any of the traceable locations mentioned at the trial.{{sfn|Douglas|1978|pp=47–48|ps=}}

