[[Category:History of Lancashire]]

[[File:Upper and Lower Black Moss Reservoir - geograph.org.uk - 106540.jpg|right|thumb|250px|[[Black Moss Reservoirs|Lower Black Moss Reservoir]] (on the left), one of the suggested sites for the location of Malkin Tower|alt=rolling unwooded landscape]]
'''Malkin Tower''', sometimes called '''Malking Tower'''{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=37|ps=}} or '''Mocking Tower''',{{sfn|Poole|2002|p=13|ps=}} was the home of Elizabeth Southerns, also known as Demdike,{{efn|name=Demdike|"Demdike" is derived from "devil woman", suggesting that Elizabeth Southerns was "feared and loathed within the community".{{sfn|Clayton|2007|p=204|ps=}}}} and her granddaughter Alizon Device,{{sfn|Froome|2010|p=38|ps=}} two of the chief protagonists in the [[Pendle witches|Lancashire witch trials]] of 1612.<ref name="Executions"/>

On [[Good Friday]], 6 April 1612, Malkin Tower was the venue for perhaps the most well-known alleged witch's coven in English legal history.{{sfn|Bennett|1993|p=22|ps=}} Eight of those who attended were arrested and tried for causing harm by witchcraft, seven of whom were found guilty and executed. The house was demolished shortly after the trials and forgotten. The only firm evidence of its location comes from the official account by the clerk to the court Thomas Potts, who says simply that it was in the Forest of Pendle. Archaeological excavations in the area have failed to discover any confirmed remains of the building.

Several explanations have been suggested for the origins of the word "Malkin", but despite its name Malkin Tower was likely to have been a simple cottage.

==History==
===Toponymy===
